WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:14.808
Percentages are great for comparing, but you don't spend
percentages, you spend dollars. This little table is the
translator. It turns every move into the cash it actually
means for your position size.

2
00:00:15.408 --> 00:00:30.408
It's Contract dollars per Move. Down the side are the
percentage moves we've been talking about this whole time.
And the two columns are what each one is actually worth,
in real dollars, at the number of contracts you're
trading. Loss dollars if it goes against you, win dollars
if it goes your way.

3
00:00:31.008 --> 00:00:45.360
So a tiny move of five hundredths of a percent is worth
this many dollars per trade. A bigger, half-percent move
is worth a lot more. It's the exact same percentages you
saw in the strike rates and the risk ladder, just
translated into money you can actually feel.

4
00:00:45.960 --> 00:01:07.128
And here's the key thing to understand. Every number in
these columns scales with one single input. Your contract
size. Double your contracts, and every dollar here doubles
with them. Your percentages don't change at all, your edge
is exactly the same, but the dollars, and the risk, scale
straight up with size. This is where percent becomes a
paycheck, and also where it becomes danger.

5
00:01:07.728 --> 00:01:20.592
This is exactly why the dashboard can take your abstract
percentage edge and tell you real things. Like, will this
pass a prop account, or how big a drawdown in dollars you
have to survive. All of it flows from this one quiet
conversion.

6
00:01:21.192 --> 00:01:28.560
Percent tells you if you even have an edge. This table
tells you what that edge is worth, and what it will cost
you, at the size you actually trade.

7
00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:34.656
Know your edge in percent. Know your risk in dollars. This
little table is the bridge between the two.
